ng indigenous, anarchist, ethnic, and feminist media -- against the backdrop of political, economic, and cultural developments in Canada. They get at the heart of alternative media by focusing on the three interconnected dimensions that define them: structure, participation, and activism. Alternative Media in Canada not only reveals how alternative media are enabled and constrained within Canada's complex media and policy environment; it also shows that, in the context of globalization, the Canadian experience parallels media and policy challenges in other nations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAlternative mass mediaxPolitical aspectszCanada. 0aAlternative mass mediaxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aAlternative mass mediazCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 aBredin, Marian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Nicole S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreeman, Barbara M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJeppesen, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarim, Karim H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKozolanka, Kirsten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKozolanka, Kirsten, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLight, Evan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLithgow, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacdonald, Sonja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMazepa, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMazepa, Patricia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMilberry, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4htt